web_results.snippet: Bamboo shoots or bamboo sprouts are the edible shoots of many bamboo species including Bambusa vulgaris and Phyllostachys edulis. They are used as vegetables in numerous Asian dishes and broths. They are sold in various processed shapes and are available in fresh, dried, and canned versions.

related_questions.question: Is eating bamboo shoots good for you?
related_questions.snippet: Bamboo shoots have immense potential of being used as important health food as they contain high proteins, amino acids, carbohydrates, many important minerals, and vitamins [12]. Freshly collected bamboo shoots have good amount of thiamine, niacin, vitamin A, vitamin B6, and vitamin E [13, 14].

related_questions.question: Who should avoid bamboo shoots?
related_questions.snippet: Bamboo shoots is one of the dishes to avoid for people with stomach pain because bamboo shoots contain a lot of cyanhydric acid (about 230mg in a kilogram of bamboo shoots). This is considered a harmful substance to the stomach, so people with stomach pain should not eat bamboo shoots.
related_questions.title: Eating bamboo shoots harmful to the stomach? - Vinmec

related_questions.question: Do I need to cook bamboo shoots?
related_questions.snippet: Preparation. Fresh bamboo shoots contain toxins that are destroyed by cooking, so be sure to blanch or boil them before use. Canned shoots are best rinsed before use. If they have a strong odour or tinny flavour, boil in fresh water for a few minutes.
related_questions.title: Bamboo shoots recipes - BBC Food

related_questions.question: Can you eat bamboo shoots raw?
related_questions.snippet: Bamboo is edible, but it must be prepared properly before consumption. Fresh bamboo contains toxins that are poisonous to humans, so it should not be eaten raw.

buttons.subtitle: Are Bamboo Shoots Good
buttons.title: Bamboo Shoots: Nutrients, Benefits, and More - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Bamboo shoots are a popular ingredient in many types of Asian cuisine. They're rich in nutrients and may be associated with several health benefits, including increased weight loss, improved digestive health, and decreased cholesterol levels.

buttons.subtitle: What Do Bamboo Shoots Taste Like
buttons.title: Fresh Bamboo Shoots Information and Facts - Specialty Produce
buttons.snippet: Fresh Bamboo shoots have a mild and sweet taste suited for cooked preparations. The shoots have a tough, woody, and bitter flavor when raw, but once parboiled or cooked, they develop a tender, crunchy, and succulent consistency with a sweeter taste.

buttons.subtitle: Bamboo Shoots Benefits
buttons.title: Bamboo: Health Benefits, Nutrients, Preparation, and More - WebMD
buttons.snippet: With high levels of fiber and very few calories per serving, bamboo shoots are a great way to lower your levels of “bad” LDL cholesterol. This, in turn, can reduce your risk of heart disease. From digestive disorders to pregnancy-related nausea, there are plenty of reasons you might want to increase your appetite.
snippet_highlighted_words: lower your levels of “bad” LDL cholesterol

buttons.subtitle: How To Cook Bamboo Shoots
buttons.title: Preparing Bamboo Shoot - Toiro Kitchen
buttons.snippet: Simmer over low heat until the thick part of a bamboo shoot is just tender when inserting a skewer. (35-40 minutes for a small to medium-size bamboo shoot.) Turn off the heat and let it cool down completely. Peel the tough leaves of each bamboo shoot to reveal the tender interior.
